Sixth-sixth Avenue, betxeen Fitchett and Alderton Streets, showing in the four vievs te homes of Baum (left foreground of view number one), Kinsey (white house just beyond the Baum house), Enoland (midway between the first two rwentioned ard on the opposite side of the street), and Springsteen'a (on te same side of the street as the Rirsey house but beyond it, in view nummber two). Vie.s three and four show a closeup of the England house and outbuildings. The above named indiiduals appear as oWners on realty maps in 1852. Their descendents have held on as owners to the beginning of the 20th century. The Sprinosteen family have an orioocinal dutch grant of 4 acres in this area dating back to the middle of tPe 17th centry. In 1928, the four acres brouaht 1,O00,O00. Edward Enggland Sr. settled here in 1853 in a hose, part of which is said to have been used as a hospital for wouuded
soldiers in tue Hevolutionary War.
Aumst 1925.

Sixty-sixth Avenue (White Pot Road, located in front of white house) between Fitchett and Alderton Streets. Shown is a rear view of J. Englands farmhouse and lands south from Sixty-sixth Avenue to Yellowstone Boulevard and from Fitchett Street to the Long Island Railroad Rockaway Beach Branch. E. J. England
was the owner in 1909.
May 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
